The Trojan horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will need to be allocated.
You will have to put conditions on that.
The Greek government will make empty promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets are going to calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be deal-breakers, but there will be problems to come.
Some will say that the fatal error was allowing Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was obvious, however, that the country was not ready.
Its fiscal policy was already uncontrolled when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pushing for Greek salaries to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of malfunctioning do not限于此希腊。改为：But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of malfunctioning are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with an unemployment rate of 20% and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as a mirror of its own future.
And if that is not the case, the markets take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing a bit better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Just like Greece, they cannot engage in currency devaluation to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Just like Greece, they will be tempted to seek aid.
All of this raises one question: was the real mistake not having created the euro?
Given that I was one of the few Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you would have every right to ask me: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, the creation of the euro was not an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway towards a viable monetary union.
If she does nothing, the next crisis could well pass this one off as a walk in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own mechanism for emergency financing.
Today, members of the Union can only help Greece by exceeding the regulations that prevent them from extending a loan, except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders offer their help, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it needs to be modified.
Moreover, aid should not be given solely under certain conditions but should be accompanied by a temporary control of the national budget by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
The history shows that simple promises issued by recipient countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries that will be subject to this kind of measure will express their indignation.
But, no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Notice that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the deceased Stability and Growth Pact.
One could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily put its budget in the hands of an expert specially appointed by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it would not bother them that much.
The expert would not be of California origin, but American.
The public opinion would understand that he acts in the interest of the California state as much as in that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from where these orders of this expert would emanate, would reassure them.
The Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they first and foremost think of themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly hesitant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political relations.
Those who have a robust emergency assistance mechanism will actually be accountable.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel despises this kind of rescue because they know well who will be left to pay for it.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles political European integration.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank not obligated to account for its actions, but which today has adopted a monetary policy that is excessively aggressive, thereby contributing to critically worsen the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The enormous current account surpluses of Germany exacerbate their situation even more.
Moreover, its fiscal stimulus measures were not sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has significantly benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should pay him back.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as the political integration needed to make it possible.
She must provide more financial support.
Isn't she the one in the best position to exert pressure for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that will lead Europe towards a more thorough political integration.
One can only hope.
